<font color="#FF0000">ASKING FOR ASSISTANCE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan 21  0:19:10 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Hello to you all, perhaps you may be able to help me out.  I am a<br>
french Canadian who has been working on a side project that arised<br>
over a conversation on Vietnam.   I am a young director living<br>
outside of Toronto, I have recently been approached to write a play<br>
dealing with the Men who went to Vietnam and their wives who stayed<br>
behind.  I have done research surrounding this issue, but as we all<br>
know, what better to hear from the ones who lived through it. <br>
I am trying to give this play a sense of realism, and for that I am<br>
asking for your assistance.  <br>
To give you some what of an ideal on the play, and the topics it <br>
will be dealing with, here is a very broad outline/summery.<br><br>
18 years after the war has ended, a vet's child falls into a box of<br>
pictures and letters that his Mother had received and gathered<br>
during the time her husband was out fighting the war.  This boy was<br>
meant to  believe that the man who has raised him throughout all<br>
his life was his natural father, a Vietnam Vet himself.  By reading<br>
the letters and going through the pictures he slowly unravels the<br>
truth and bringing to life the past that his mother has tried so<br>
hard to forget, who and what his father was.  <br>
Everything from then on is a flashback bringing you back to 1969 in<br>
the heart of Vietnam.  It will touch on the draft, and events that<br>
went on in the lives of the men at war, and the wives and families<br>
left behind.  In the letters he will learn and meet the men his<br>
father has met and friendship he has made, and he will then<br>
understand the hidden brutality of the war, and the fallen warriors<br>
who fought it. But all this soon collapse for the young boy as he<br>
reads the final letter sent to his mother announcing the death of<br>
her husband.   It will then go into the pain and suffering she<br>
endured afterwards.  <br>
One year after the Child was born, she gets a visit from a stranger<br>
who claimed that he served with her husband, within that stay he<br>
relives that final night and confronts in her, telling her how much<br>
good she was doing for her husband and all the men by writing them<br>
simple letters that she sent out.  For as much as she was writing<br>
for only him she was also writing to all the men in his platoon,<br>
for they found peace and sanity in her words as they were read out<br>
loud around the fires.  When it was time for him to leave and head<br>
back home, it was to late for both of them, love had taking over. <br>
 <br>
The play is then brought back into the present time and the boy is<br>
now faced with the truth about his father.   confused, lost and<br>
hurt, he confronts in his mother and she goes on to end the play<br>
with a final letter that her husband wrote, this was given to her<br>
17 years ago by the husband she now has, the day they fell in love.<br>
  <br>
To be more specific on what I am asking from you, here is a list of<br>
things that may help you out. <br>
Actual letters that where written, what the letter may have<br>
consisted or dealt with, and personal feelings on both parties when<br>
the letters where received.  I am also asking for stories or events<br>
that you all had to live through each day down there, simple task's<br>
that where asked of you all.  Anything dealing with a death of a<br>
close friend, and everyday pain.  <br>
I understand what this is asking of you all, and to keep this<br>
personal and confidential you may send any information that you<br>
think will help in bringing reality to this play.  Please fell free<br>
to email me at this address, lavoie@mnsi.net<br>
You must understand you are giving me this information on your own<br>
free will and anything that will be used, you will be contacted and<br>
a copy will be sent to you. If you are in need to write I am here<br>
to listen.<br><br>
I thank you for all your help and hope to hear something from you<br>
all.<br>
God bless you all.  
